# Shuffle the Dataset.

shuffled_df = df.sample(frac=1,random_state=4)



# Put all the fraud class in a separate dataset.

True_df = shuffled_df.loc[shuffled_df['Target'] == 1]



#Randomly select 492 observations from the non-fraud (majority class)

False_df = shuffled_df.loc[shuffled_df['Target'] == 0].sample(n=5289,random_state=42)



# Concatenate both dataframes again

normalized_df = pd.concat([True_df, False_df])



#plot the dataset after the undersampling

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))

sns.countplot('Target', data=normalized_df)

plt.title('Balanced Targer')

plt.show()

For this dataset, Random forest and bagging models give the best results on test predictions

Best Algorithm - Bagging with 86% Accuracy Score is the clear winner but as we can see Random Forest and Gradient Boost also the winner candidates if we can further tune down the algorithm. ¶

One thing is very clear if we compare the result from one model (Decision Tree - 77%) versus Ensemble techniques using multiple models (81% + Accuracy) we have better accuracy from Ensemble Techniques.¶

One more thing I have realized with this project is that Exploratory data analysis and prepare the dataset for the algorithm is the most important steps in-order to achieve high accuracy.¶
